ma theory and documentary studies, Noah Tsika argues that trauma was foundational in postwar American culture. Examining wartime and postwar debates about the use of cinema as a vehicle for studying, publicizing, and even what has been termed “working through” war trauma, this book is an original contribution to scholarship on the military-industrial complex.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDocumentary filmsxTherapeutic use. 0aNonfiction filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aPsychoanalysis and motion pictures. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xMotion pictures and the war. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPsychological aspects. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096992640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969926423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520969926/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles